In object-oriented programming, the `override` keyword is used in many programming languages to indicate that a subclass method is intended to perform the same function as a method in its superclass with the same name, signature, and return type. This allows the subclass to provide its own implementation of an existing method in the superclass.

Here are some guidelines for using `override` safely:

1. **Check the superclass method**: Before overriding a method, make sure you understand what the method does in the superclass and why it was implemented that way. This will help you determine whether you need to change the behavior of the method in the subclass and how to do so effectively.
2. **Maintain compatibility**: When overriding a method, ensure that the method signature (name, parameters, return type) is compatible with the superclass method. If the method signature changes, it may break existing code that relies on the original implementation of the method.
3. **Consider the impact on subclasses**: If you override a method in a superclass, any subclasses of the superclass will inherit the overridden method instead of the original method. This means that any behavior changes you make to the method may affect all subclasses that inherit it. Be mindful of this when making changes and consider providing an option for subclasses to opt-out of the new behavior if necessary.
4. **Document your changes**: When overriding a method, be sure to document your changes clearly so that other developers can understand why you made the changes and how they affect the behavior of the method. This will help prevent confusion and make it easier for others to work with your code.
5. **Test thoroughly**: After overriding a method, test it thoroughly to ensure that it works as intended and does not introduce any new bugs or unexpected behavior. This may involve writing unit tests or integration tests to verify the correctness of the method in various scenarios.
6. **Consider using `final`**: If you do not want subclasses to override a method, you can declare the method as `final` in the superclass. This prevents any subclasses from overriding the method and ensures that the behavior remains consistent across all instances of the class hierarchy.
